Brothers Lewis and Shadrack Oichoe dominated the short races during the Nyanza North track and field event at Moi Stadium, Kisumu on Saturday. Lewis clinched the 100m and 200m titles while his elder brother Shadrak won the 400m race. In 200m, Lewis won in 21.00 beating Shadrack to second place in 21.60. Lewis clocked 10:40 to win the 100m finals ahead of Edward Omondi who crossed the finishing line in 11:00. In 400m, Lewis had a dominant performance to win the race in 50:00 with Wycliffe Omondi coming home second in 51:08. Miriam Tanui won the 400m in 1:07.05 narrowly beating Paradise Okoth to second place in 1:09.09. Tanui claimed her second title of the day winning the 800m race in 2:33.30 with Emily Achieng coming home second in 3:00.00. Speaking after the race, Lewis said he wants to follow the footsteps of his idol, Jamaican sprinter Usain Bolt. “I discovered my career after campus but I’m determined to one day represent Kenya. Bolt is my idol because he is a tall sprinter like me and he has achieved a lot,” said Lewis . “I have been training with the Prisons team, which has helped me improve on my time.” Shadrack said: “I had been busy at Kenya Polytechnic where I was doing my attachment and that I have finished, I will focus on thorough training ahead of the national Championships. ” Junior international Beatrice Odero won both the 100m and 200m races. She easily won 100m in 12.30, edging Mary Achieng in 13.10 while Ivy Awuor completed the podium in 13.50. In 200m, she won in 25.06, beating Ivy Awuor to second place in 28.01. Odero decried lack of training facilities and coaches in Homa Bay. “I train on my own in Homa Bay, where there are no training facilities. Even here in Kisumu, we have no facilities but we continue to work hard. There are many sprinters in Homa Bay but they lack exposure,” said Odero. Godwin Odhiambo won the men’s 800m title in 1:56.00, followed by Victor Otieno in 2:02.30. Kipsang Kitur beat a strong field of 20 athletes to win the 1, 500m race followed by Kipchirchir Keter. In the women’s category, Brandy Adhiambo emerged champion in 6:20.09 ahead of Alice Akello (6:43.05) . Nyanza region Athletics Kenya public relations officer Jared Gilo said they have selected a team of 25 to represent the region at the national championships at Moi International Sports Centre, Kasarani. Alvins Onyango is the head coach while Sospeter Odundo was named the team manager.